{{Starbox short | name=12 Camelopardalis {{Starbox image | image = [[Image:12 Camelopardalis.jpg|250px]] | caption = 12 Camelopardalis in optical light }} | epoch=[[J2000.0]] | constell=[[Camelopardalis]] | ra={{RA|05|06|12.2}} | dec={{DEC|+59|01|16}} | spectral=K0III | appmag_v=+6.08 | absmag_v=−0.332<ref name=BohmVitense2000/> | dist_ly=625 ± 110 | dist_pc=192 ± 34 | names=BM&nbsp;Camelopardalis, [[Harvard Revised catalogue|HR]]&nbsp;1623, [[Henry Draper Catalogue|HD]]&nbsp;32357, [[Bonner Durchmusterung|BD]]+58°805, [[Hipparcos catalogue|HIP]]&nbsp;23743, [[Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory catalogue|SAO]]&nbsp;25003, GC&nbsp;6197, BDS&nbsp;2480, CCDM&nbsp;05062+5900 }} '''12 Camelopardalis''' is a [[spectroscopic binary]]<ref name=Pourbaix>{{ cite journal |display-authors=6 |author=Pourbaix D |author2=Tokovinin AA |author3=Batten AH |author4=Fekel FC |author5=Hartkopf WI |author6=Levato H |author7=Morrell NI |author8=Torres G |author9=Udry S |title=S<sub>B</sub><sup>9</sup>: The ninth cataloque of spectroscopic binary orbits |journal=Astron Astrophys |date=Sep 2004 |volume=424 |issue=2 |pages=727–732 |doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20041213 |url=http://cds.aanda.org/index.php?option=article&access=bibcode&bibcode=2004A%2526A...424..727P |bibcode=2004A&A...424..727P|arxiv = astro-ph/0406573 }}</ref> in the [[constellation]] [[Camelopardalis]]. It also forms a [[double star]] with [[11 Camelopardalis]], which is only 3 arcminutes away.
12 Camelopardalis is classified as an orange [[stellar classification|K-type]] [[giant star|giant]] with a mean [[apparent magnitude]] of +6.08. The binary is an [[RS Canum Venaticorum variable|RS Canum Venaticorum type]] [[variable star]] and its brightness varies by 0.14 magnitudes with a period of 82.8 days. The [[orbital period]] of the binary is 80.174 days. 12 Camelopardalis is approximately 625 [[light years]] from [[Earth]].
==X-ray source==
BM Cam also emits X-rays and is the designated X-ray source 1H 0501+592.<ref name=Wood>{{ cite journal |author=Wood KS |author2=Meekins JF |author3=Yentis DJ |author4=Smathers HW |author5=McNutt DP |author6=Bleach RD |title=The HEAO A-1 X-ray source catalog |journal=Astrophys. J. Suppl. Ser. |date=Dec 1984 |volume=56 |issue=12 |pages=507–649 |bibcode=1984ApJS...56..507W |doi=10.1086/190992 }}</ref> It has been detected by [[HEAO 1]], the [[Einstein Observatory]], and [[ROSAT]].
